# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: polymerization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Propagation: The initiator fragment reacts with a monomer M to begin the conversion to the polymer; the center of activity is retained in the adduct.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chain transfer: The active species is transferred to another molecule, e.g. solvent, polymeric chain, monomer, etc via transfer of a group or an atom (e.g.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chain transfer may or may not occur depending on the nature of the reactive species.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In 1953, Paul Flory first classified polymerization as "step-growth polymerization" and "chain-growth polymerization".
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] IUPAC recommends to further simplify "chain-growth polymerization" to "chain polymerization".
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] It is a kind of polymerization where an active center (free radical or ion) is formed, and a plurality of monomers can be polymerized together in a short period of time to form a macromolecule having a large molecular weight.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In addition to the regenerated active sites of each monomer unit, polymer growth will only occur at one (or possibly more) endpoint.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Many common polymers can be obtained by chain polymerization such as polyethylene (PE), polypropylene (PP), polyvinyl chloride (PVC), poly(methyl methacrylate) (PMMA), polyacrylonitrile (PAN), polyvinyl acetate (PVA).
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In this equation, P is the polymer while x represents degree of polymerization, * means active center of chain-growth polymerization, M is the monomer which will react with active center, and L may be a low-molar-mass by-product obtained during chain propagation.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] For most chain-growth polymerizations, there is no by-product L formed.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] However there are some exceptions, such as the polymerization of amino acid *N*-carboxyanhydrides to oxazolidine-2,5-diones.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The word "chain" here does not refer to the fact that polymer molecules form long chains.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Some polymers are formed instead by a second type of mechanism known as step-growth polymerization without rapid chain propagation steps.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] All chain-growth polymerization reactions must include chain initiation and chain propagation.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chain transfer and chain termination steps also occur in many but not all chain-growth polymerizations.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chain initiation is the initial generation of a chain carrier, which is an intermediate such as a radical or an ion which can continue the reaction by chain propagation.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Initiation steps are classified according to the way that energy is provided: thermal initiation, high energy initiation, and chemical initiation, etc.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Thermal initiation uses molecular thermal motion to dissociate a molecule and form active centers.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] High energy initiation refers to the generation of chain carriers by radiation.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chemical initiation is due to a chemical initiator.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] For the case of radical polymerization as an example, chain initiation involves the dissociation of a radical initiator molecule (I) which is easily dissociated by heat or light into two free radicals (2 R°).
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Each radical R° then adds a first monomer molecule (M) to start a chain which terminates with a monomer activated by the presence of an unpaired electron (RM1°).
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] IUPAC defines chain propagation as a reaction of an active center on the growing polymer molecule, which adds one monomer molecule to form a new polymer molecule (RM1°) one repeat unit longer.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] For radical polymerization, the active center remains an atom with an unpaired electron.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] For some polymers, chains of over 1000 monomer units can be formed in milliseconds.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In a chain termination step, the active center disappears, resulting in the termination of chain propagation.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] This is different from chain transfer in which the active center only shifts to another molecule but does not disappear.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] For radical polymerization, termination involves a reaction of two growing polymer chains to eliminate the unpaired electrons of both chains.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Initiation, propagation and termination steps also occur in chain reactions of smaller molecules.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] This is not true of the chain transfer and branching steps considered next.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In some chain-growth polymerizations there is also a chain transfer step, in which the growing polymer chain RMn° takes an atom X from an inactive molecule XY, terminating the growth of the polymer chain: RMn° + XY → RMnX + Y°.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The Y fragment ls a new active center which adds more monomer M to form a new growing chain YMn°.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] This can happen in free radical polymerization for chains RMn°, in ionic polymerization for chains RMn+ or RMn–, or in coordination polymerization.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In most cases chain transfer will generate a by-product and decrease the molar mass of the final polymer.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Another possibility is chain transfer to a second polymer molecule, result in the formation of a product macromolecule with a branched structure.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In this case the growing chain takes an atom X from a second polymer chain whose growth had been completed.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The growth of the first polymer chain is completed by the transfer of atom X.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] However the second molecule loses an atom X from the interior of its polymer chain to form a reactive radical (or ion) which can add more monomer molecules.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] This results in the addition of a branch or side chain and the formation of a product macromolecule with a branched structure.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) recommends definitions for several classes of chain-growth polymerization.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Based on the IUPAC definition, radical polymerization is a chain polymerization in which the kinetic-chain carriers are radicals.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Usually, the growing chain end bears an unpaired electron.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Free radicals can be initiated by many methods such as heating, redox reactions, ultraviolet radiation, high energy irradiation, electrolysis, sonication, and plasma.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Free radical polymerization is very important in polymer chemistry.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] It is one of the most developed methods in chain-growth polymerization.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Currently, most polymers in our daily life are synthesized by free radical polymerization, including polyethylene, polystyrene, polyvinyl chloride, polymethyl methacrylate, polyacrylonitrile, polyvinyl acetate, styrene butadiene rubber, nitrile rubber, neoprene, etc.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Ionic polymerization is a chain polymerization in which the kinetic-chain carriers are ions or ion pairs.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] It can be further divided into anionic polymerization and cationic polymerization.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Ionic polymerization generates many polymers used in daily life, such as butyl rubber, polyisobutylene, polyphenylene, polyoxymethylene, polysiloxane, polyethylene oxide, high density polyethylene, isotactic polypropylene, butadiene rubber, etc.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Living anionic polymerization was developed in the 1950s.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The chain will remain active indefinitely unless the reaction is transferred or terminated deliberately, which allows the control of molar weight and dispersity (or polydispersity index, PDI).
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Coordination polymerization is a chain polymerization that involves the preliminary coordination of a monomer molecule with a chain carrier.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The monomer is first coordinated with the transition metal active center, and then the activated monomer is inserted into the transition metal-carbon bond for chain growth.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In some cases, coordination polymerization is also called insertion polymerization or complexing polymerization.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Advanced coordination polymerizations can control the tacticity, molecular weight and PDI of the polymer effectively.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In addition, the racemic mixture of the chiral metallocene can be separated into its enantiomers.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The oligomerization reaction produces an optically active branched olefin using an optically active catalyst.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Living polymerization was first described by Michael Szwarc in 1956.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] It is defined as a chain polymerization from which chain transfer and chain termination are absent.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In the absence of chain-transfer and chain termination, the monomer in the system is consumed and the polymerization stops but the polymer chain remains active.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] If new monomer is added, the polymerization can proceed.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Due to the low PDI and predictable molecular weight, living polymerization is at the forefront of polymer research.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] It can be further divided into living free radical polymerization, living ionic polymerization and living ring-opening metathesis polymerization, etc.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Ring-opening polymerization is defined as a polymerization in which a cyclic monomer yields a monomeric unit which is acyclic or contains fewer cycles than the monomer.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Generally, the ring-opening polymerization is carried out under mild conditions, and the by-product is less than in the polycondensation reaction.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] A high molecular weight polymer is easily obtained.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Common ring-opening polymerization products includes polypropylene oxide, polytetrahydrofuran, polyepichlorohydrin, polyoxymethylene, polycaprolactam and polysiloxane.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Reversible-deactivation polymerization is defined as a chain polymerization propagated by chain carriers that are deactivated reversibly, bringing them into one or more active-dormant equilibria.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] An example of a reversible-deactivation polymerization is group-transfer polymerization.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Polymers were first classified according to polymerization method by Wallace Carothers in 1929, who introduced the terms addition polymer and condensation polymer to describe polymers made by addition reactions and condensation reactions respectively.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] However this classification is inadequate to describe a polymer which can be made by either type of reaction, for example nylon 6 which can be made either by addition of a cyclic monomer or by condensation of a linear monomer.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Flory revised the classification to chain-growth polymerization and step-growth polymerization, based on polymerization mechanisms rather than polymer structures.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] IUPAC now recommends that the names of step-growth polymerization and chain-growth polymerization be further simplified to polycondensation (or polyaddition if no low-molar-mass by-product is formed when a monomer is added) and chain polymerization.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Most polymerizations are either chain-growth or step-growth reactions.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chain-growth includes both initiation and propagation steps (at least), and the propagation of chain-growth polymers proceeds by the addition of monomers to a growing polymer with an active centre.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In contrast step-growth polymerization involves only one type of step, and macromolecules can grow by reaction steps between any two molecular species: two monomers, a monomer and a growing chain, or two growing chains.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In step growth, the monomers will initially form dimers, trimers, etc. which later react to form long chain polymers.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In chain-growth polymerization, a growing macromolecule increases in size rapidly once its growth is initiated.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] When a macromolecule stops growing it generally will add no more monomers.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In step-growth polymerization on the other hand, a single polymer molecule can grow over the course of the whole reaction.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In chain-growth polymerization, long macromolecules with high molecular weight are formed when only a small fraction of monomer has reacted.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Monomers are consumed steadily over the course of the whole reaction, but the degree of polymerization can increase very quickly after chain initiation.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] However in step-growth polymerization the monomer is consumed very quickly to dimer, trimer and oligomer.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The degree of polymerization increases steadily during the whole polymerization process.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] The type of polymerization of a given monomer usually depends on the functional groups present, and sometimes also on whether the monomer is linear or cyclic.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chain-growth polymers are usually addition polymers by Carothers' definition.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] They are typically formed by addition reactions of C=C bonds in the monomer backbone, which contains only carbon-carbon bonds.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Another possibility is ring-opening polymerization, as for the chain-growth polymerization of tetrahydrofuran or of polycaprolactone (see Introduction above).
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Step-growth polymers are typically condensation polymers in which an elimination product as such as H2O are formed.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Examples are polyamides, polycarbonates, polyesters, polyimides, polysiloxanes and polysulfones.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] If no elimination product is formed, then the polymer is an addition polymer, such as a polyurethane or a poly(phenylene oxide).
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chain-growth polymerization with a low-molar-mass by-product during chain growth is described by IUPAC as "condensative chain polymerization".
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Compared to step-growth polymerization, living chain-growth polymerization shows low molar mass dispersity (or PDI), predictable molar mass distribution and controllable conformation.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Generally, polycondensation proceeds in a step-growth polymerization mode.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Chain polymerization products are widely used in many aspects of life, including electronic devices, food packaging, catalyst carriers, medical materials, etc.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] At present, the world's highest yielding polymers such as polyethylene (PE), polyvinyl chloride (PVC), polypropylene (PP), etc. can be obtained by chain polymerization.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] In addition, some carbon nanotube polymer is used for electronical devices.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Controlled living chain-growth conjugated polymerization will also enable the synthesis of well-defined advanced structures, including block copolymers.
[src:polymerization/chain-growth-polymerization] Their industrial applications extend to water purification, biomedical devices and sensors.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] In polymer chemistry, **emulsion polymerization** is a type of radical polymerization that usually starts with an emulsion incorporating water, monomers, and surfactants.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The most common type of emulsion polymerization is an oil-in-water emulsion, in which droplets of monomer (the oil) are emulsified (with surfactants) in a continuous phase of water.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Water-soluble polymers, such as certain polyvinyl alcohols or hydroxyethyl cellulose, can also be used to act as emulsifiers/stabilizers.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The name "emulsion polymerization" is a misnomer that arises from a historical misconception.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Rather than occurring in emulsion droplets, polymerization takes place in the latex/colloid particles that form spontaneously in the first few minutes of the process.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] These latex particles are typically 100 nm in size, and are made of many individual polymer chains.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The particles are prevented from coagulating with each other because each particle is surrounded by the surfactant ('soap'); the charge on the surfactant repels other particles electrostatically.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] When water-soluble polymers are used as stabilizers instead of soap, the repulsion between particles arises because these water-soluble polymers form a 'hairy layer' around a particle that repels other particles, because pushing particles together would involve compressing these chains.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Emulsion polymerization is used to make several commercially important polymers.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Many of these polymers are used as solid materials and must be isolated from the aqueous dispersion after polymerization.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] In other cases the dispersion itself is the end product.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] A dispersion resulting from emulsion polymerization is often called a latex (especially if derived from a synthetic rubber) or an emulsion (even though "emulsion" strictly speaking refers to a dispersion of an immiscible liquid in water).
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] These emulsions find applications in adhesives, paints, paper coating and textile coatings.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] They are often preferred over solvent-based products in these applications due to the absence of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) in them.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The early history of emulsion polymerization is connected with the field of synthetic rubber.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The idea of using an emulsified monomer in an aqueous suspension or emulsion was first conceived at Bayer, before World War I, in an attempt to prepare synthetic rubber.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The impetus for this development was the observation that natural rubber is produced at room temperature in dispersed particles stabilized by colloidal polymers, so the industrial chemists tried to duplicate these conditions.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The Bayer workers used naturally occurring polymers such as gelatin, ovalbumin, and starch to stabilize their dispersion.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] By today's definition these were not true emulsion polymerizations, but suspension polymerizations.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The first "true" emulsion polymerizations, which used a surfactant and polymerization initiator, were conducted in the 1920s to polymerize isoprene.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] After World War II, emulsion polymerization was extended to production of plastics.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Manufacture of dispersions to be used in latex paints and other products sold as liquid dispersions commenced.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Ever more sophisticated processes were devised to prepare products that replaced solvent-based materials.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Ironically, synthetic rubber manufacture turned more and more away from emulsion polymerization as new organometallic catalysts were developed that allowed much better control of polymer architecture.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The first successful theory to explain the distinct features of emulsion polymerization was developed by Smith and Ewart, and Harkins in the 1940s, based on their studies of polystyrene.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Smith and Ewart arbitrarily divided the mechanism of emulsion polymerization into three stages or intervals.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Subsequently, it has been recognized that not all monomers or systems undergo these particular three intervals.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Nevertheless, the Smith-Ewart description is a useful starting point to analyze emulsion polymerizations.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Smith-Ewart theory does not predict the specific polymerization behavior when the monomer is somewhat water-soluble, like methyl methacrylate or vinyl acetate.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] In these cases homogeneous nucleation occurs: particles are formed without the presence or need for surfactant micelles.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] High molecular weights are developed in emulsion polymerization because the concentration of growing chains within each polymer particle is very low.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] In conventional radical polymerization, the concentration of growing chains is higher, which leads to termination by coupling, which ultimately results in shorter polymer chains.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The original Smith-Ewart-Hawkins mechanism required each particle to contain either zero or one growing chain.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Improved understanding of emulsion polymerization has relaxed that criterion to include more than one growing chain per particle, however, the number of growing chains per particle is still considered to be very low.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Because of the complex chemistry that occurs during an emulsion polymerization, including polymerization kinetics and particle formation kinetics, quantitative understanding of the mechanism of emulsion polymerization has required extensive computer simulation.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Robert Gilbert has summarized a recent theory.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] When radicals generated in the aqueous phase encounter the monomer within the micelle, they initiate polymerization.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The conversion of monomer to polymer within the micelle lowers the monomer concentration and generates a monomer concentration gradient.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Consequently, the monomer from monomer droplets and uninitiated micelles begin to diffuse to the growing, polymer-containing, particles.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Those micelles that did not encounter a radical during the earlier stage of conversion begin to disappear, losing their monomer and surfactant to the growing particles.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The theory predicts that after the end of this interval, the number of growing polymer particles remains constant.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] This interval is also known as steady state reaction stage.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Throughout this stage, monomer droplets act as reservoirs supplying monomer to the growing polymer particles by diffusion through the water.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] While at steady state, the ratio of free radicals per particle can be divided into three cases.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] When the number of free radicals per particle is less than 1⁄2, this is called Case 1.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] When the number of free radicals per particle equals 1⁄2, this is called Case 2.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] And when there is greater than 1⁄2 radical per particle, this is called Case 3.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Smith-Ewart theory predicts that Case 2 is the predominant scenario for the following reasons.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] A monomer-swollen particle that has been struck by a radical contains one growing chain.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Because only one radical (at the end of the growing polymer chain) is present, the chain cannot terminate, and it will continue to grow until a second initiator radical enters the particle.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] As the rate of termination is much greater than the rate of propagation, and because the polymer particles are extremely small, chain growth is terminated immediately after the entrance of the second initiator radical.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The particle then remains dormant until a third initiator radical enters, initiating the growth of a second chain.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Consequently, the polymer particles in this case either have zero radicals (dormant state), or 1 radical (polymer growing state) and a very short period of 2 radicals (terminating state) which can be ignored for the free radicals per particle calculation.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] At any given time, a micelle contains either one growing chain or no growing chains (assumed to be equally probable).
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Thus, on average, there is around 1/2 radical per particle, leading to the Case 2 scenario.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] $[\mathrm {P} ^{\bullet }]={\frac {N_{\mathrm {micelles} }}{2N_{\mathrm {A} }}}$ where $N_{\mathrm {micelles} }$ is number concentration of micelles (number of micelles per unit volume), and $N_{\mathrm {A} }$ is the Avogadro constant (6.02×1023 mol−1).
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Separate monomer droplets disappear as the reaction continues.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Polymer particles in this stage may be sufficiently large enough that they contain more than 1 radical per particle.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Emulsion polymerizations have been used in batch, semi-batch, and continuous processes.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The choice depends on the properties desired in the final polymer or dispersion and on the economics of the product.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Modern process control schemes have enabled the development of complex reaction processes, with ingredients such as initiator, monomer, and surfactant added at the beginning, during, or at the end of the reaction.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Early styrene-butadiene rubber (SBR) recipes are examples of true batch processes: all ingredients added at the same time to the reactor.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Semi-batch recipes usually include a programmed feed of monomer to the reactor.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] This enables a starve-fed reaction to ensure a good distribution of monomers into the polymer backbone chain.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Continuous processes have been used to manufacture various grades of synthetic rubber.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Some polymerizations are stopped before all the monomer has reacted.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] This minimizes chain transfer to polymer.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] In such cases the monomer must be removed or stripped from the dispersion.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Colloidal stability is a factor in design of an emulsion polymerization process.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] For dry or isolated products, the polymer dispersion must be isolated, or converted into solid form.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] This can be accomplished by simple heating of the dispersion until all water evaporates.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] More commonly, the dispersion is destabilized (sometimes called "broken") by addition of a multivalent cation.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Alternatively, acidification will destabilize a dispersion with a carboxylic acid surfactant.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] These techniques may be employed in combination with application of shear to increase the rate of destabilization.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] After isolation of the polymer, it is usually washed, dried, and packaged.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] By contrast, products sold as a dispersion are designed with a high degree of colloidal stability.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Colloidal properties such as particle size, particle size distribution, and viscosity are of critical importance to the performance of these dispersions.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Living polymerization processes that are carried out via emulsion polymerization such as iodine-transfer polymerization and RAFT have been developed.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Controlled coagulation techniques can enable better control of the particle size and distribution.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Typical monomers are those that undergo radical polymerization, are liquid or gaseous at reaction conditions, and are poorly soluble in water.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Solid monomers are difficult to disperse in water.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] If monomer solubility is too high, particle formation may not occur and the reaction kinetics reduce to that of solution polymerization.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Ethene and other simple olefins must be polymerized at very high pressures (up to 800 bar).
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Copolymerization is common in emulsion polymerization.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The same rules and comonomer pairs that exist in radical polymerization operate in emulsion polymerization.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] However, copolymerization kinetics are greatly influenced by the aqueous solubility of the monomers.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Monomers with greater aqueous solubility will tend to partition in the aqueous phase and not in the polymer particle.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] They will not get incorporated as readily in the polymer chain as monomers with lower aqueous solubility.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] This can be avoided by a programmed addition of monomer using a semi-batch process.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Ethene and other alkenes are used as minor comonomers in emulsion polymerization, notably in vinyl acetate copolymers.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Small amounts of acrylic acid or other ionizable monomers are sometimes used to confer colloidal stability to a dispersion.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Both thermal and redox generation of free radicals have been used in emulsion polymerization.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Persulfate salts are commonly used in both initiation modes.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] The persulfate ion readily breaks up into sulfate radical ions above about 50°C, providing a thermal source of initiation.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Redox initiation takes place when an oxidant such as a persulfate salt, a reducing agent such as glucose, Rongalite, or sulfite, and a redox catalyst such as an iron compound are all included in the polymerization recipe.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Redox recipes are not limited by temperature and are used for polymerizations that take place below 50°C.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Although organic peroxides and hydroperoxides are used in emulsion polymerization, initiators are usually water soluble and partition into the water phase.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] This enables the particle generation behavior described in the theory section.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] In redox initiation, either the oxidant or the reducing agent (or both) must be water-soluble, but one component can be water-insoluble.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Selection of the correct surfactant is critical to the development of any emulsion polymerization process.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Anionic, nonionic, and cationic surfactants have been used, although anionic surfactants are by far most prevalent.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Mixtures of surfactants are often used, including mixtures of anionic with nonionic surfactants.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Mixtures of cationic and anionic surfactants form insoluble salts and are not useful.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Examples of surfactants commonly used in emulsion polymerization include fatty acids, sodium lauryl sulfate, and alpha-olefin sulfonate.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Some grades of polyvinyl alcohol and other water-soluble polymers can promote emulsion polymerization even though they do not typically form micelles and do not act as surfactants (for example, they do not lower surface tension).
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] It is believed that growing polymer chains graft onto these water-soluble polymers, which stabilize the resulting particles.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Dispersions prepared with such stabilizers typically exhibit excellent colloidal stability (for example, dry powders may be mixed into the dispersion without causing coagulation).
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] However, they often result in products that are very water sensitive due to the presence of the water-soluble polymer.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Other ingredients found in emulsion polymerization include chain transfer agents, buffering agents, and inert salts.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Preservatives are added to products sold as liquid dispersions to retard bacterial growth.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] These are usually added after polymerization, however.
[src:polymerization/emulsion-polymerization] Polymers produced by emulsion polymerization can roughly be divided into three categories.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In polymer chemistry, **polymerization** (American English), or **polymerisation** (British English), is a process of reacting monomer molecules together in a chemical reaction to form polymer chains or three-dimensional networks.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] There are many forms of polymerization and different systems exist to categorize them.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In chemical compounds, polymerization can occur via a variety of reaction mechanisms that vary in complexity due to the functional groups present in the reactants and their inherent steric effects.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In more straightforward polymerizations, alkenes form polymers through relatively simple radical reactions; in contrast, reactions involving substitution at a carbonyl group require more complex synthesis due to the way in which reactants polymerize.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In general, polymers such as PVC are referred to as "**homopolymers**", as they consist of repeated long chains or structures of the same monomer unit, whereas polymers that consist of more than one monomer unit are referred to as copolymers (or co-polymers).
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Such small polymers are referred to as oligomers.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Polymerization that is not sufficiently moderated and proceeds at a fast rate can be very dangerous.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] This phenomenon is known as autoacceleration, and can cause fires and explosions.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Step-growth and chain-growth are the main classes of polymerization reaction mechanisms.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] The former is often easier to implement but requires precise control of stoichiometry.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] The latter more reliably affords high molecular-weight polymers, but only applies to certain monomers.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In step-growth (or step) polymerization, pairs of reactants, of any lengths, combine at each step to form a longer polymer molecule.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] The average molar mass increases slowly.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Long chains form only late in the reaction.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Step-growth polymers are formed by independent reaction steps between functional groups of monomer units, usually containing heteroatoms such as nitrogen or oxygen.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Most step-growth polymers are also classified as condensation polymers, since a small molecule such as water is lost when the polymer chain is lengthened.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] For example, polyester chains grow by reaction of alcohol and carboxylic acid groups to form ester links with loss of water.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] However, there are exceptions; for example polyurethanes are step-growth polymers formed from isocyanate and alcohol bifunctional monomers) without loss of water or other volatile molecules, and are classified as addition polymers rather than condensation polymers.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Step-growth polymers increase in molecular weight very slowly at low conversion and reach moderately high molecular weights only at very high conversion (i.e., >95%).
[src:polymerization/polymerization] **Solid state polymerization** to afford polyamides (e.g., nylons) is an example of step-growth polymerization.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In chain-growth (or chain) polymerization, the only chain-extension reaction step is the addition of a monomer to a growing chain with an active center such as a free radical, cation, or anion.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Once the growth of a chain is initiated by formation of an active center, chain propagation is usually rapid by addition of a sequence of monomers.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Long chains are formed from the beginning of the reaction.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Chain-growth polymerization (or addition polymerization) involves the linking together of unsaturated monomers, particularly those containing carbon-carbon double bonds.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] The pi-bond is lost by formation of a new sigma bond.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Chain-growth polymerization is involved in the manufacture of polymers such as polyethylene, polypropylene, polyvinyl chloride (PVC), and acrylate.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In these cases, the alkenes RCH=CH2 are converted to high molecular weight alkanes (-RCHCH2-)n (R = H, CH3, Cl, CO2CH3).
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Other forms of chain growth polymerization include cationic addition polymerization and anionic addition polymerization.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] A special case of chain-growth polymerization leads to living polymerization.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Ziegler–Natta polymerization allows considerable control of polymer branching.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Diverse methods are employed to manipulate the initiation, propagation, and termination rates during chain polymerization.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] A related issue is temperature control, also called heat management, during these reactions, which are often highly exothermic.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] For example, for the polymerization of ethylene, 93.6 kJ of energy are released per mole of monomer.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] The manner in which polymerization is conducted is a highly evolved technology.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Methods include emulsion polymerization, solution polymerization, suspension polymerization, and precipitation polymerization.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Although the polymer dispersity and molecular weight may be improved, these methods may introduce additional processing requirements to isolate the product from a solvent.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Most **photopolymerization** reactions are chain-growth polymerizations which are initiated by the absorption of visible or ultraviolet light.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Photopolymerization can also be a step-growth polymerization.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] The light may be absorbed either directly by the reactant monomer (*direct* photopolymerization), or else by a *photosensitizer* which absorbs the light and then transfers energy to the monomer.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In general, only the initiation step differs from that of the ordinary thermal polymerization of the same monomer; subsequent propagation, termination, and chain-transfer steps are unchanged.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] In step-growth photopolymerization, absorption of light triggers an addition (or condensation) reaction between two comonomers that do not react without light.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] A propagation cycle is not initiated because each growth step requires the assistance of light.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Photopolymerization can be used as a photographic or printing process because polymerization only occurs in regions which have been exposed to light.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Unreacted monomer can be removed from unexposed regions, leaving a relief polymeric image.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Several forms of 3D printing—including layer-by-layer stereolithography and two-photon absorption 3D photopolymerization—use photopolymerization.
[src:polymerization/polymerization] Multiphoton polymerization using single pulses have also been demonstrated for fabrication of complex structures using a digital micromirror device.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] In polymer chemistry, **radical polymerization** (**RP**) is a method of polymerization by which a polymer forms by the successive addition of a radical to building blocks (repeat units).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Radicals can be formed by a number of different mechanisms, usually involving separate initiator molecules.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Following its generation, the initiating radical adds (nonradical) monomer units, thereby growing the polymer chain.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Radical polymerization is a key synthesis route for obtaining a wide variety of different polymers and materials composites.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The relatively non-specific nature of radical chemical interactions makes this one of the most versatile forms of polymerization available and allows facile reactions of polymeric radical chain ends and other chemicals or substrates.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] In 2001, 40 billion of the 110 billion pounds of polymers produced in the United States were produced by radical polymerization.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Radical polymerization is a type of chain polymerization, along with anionic, cationic and coordination polymerization.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Initiation is the first step of the polymerization process.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] During initiation, an active center is created from which a polymer chain is generated.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Not all monomers are susceptible to all types of initiators.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Radical initiation works best on the carbon–carbon double bond of vinyl monomers and the carbon–oxygen double bond in aldehydes and ketones.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] In the first step, one or two radicals are created from the initiating molecules.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] In the second step, radicals are transferred from the initiator molecules to the monomer units present.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Several choices are available for these initiators.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] cleaved, producing two radicals (Figure 1).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Radiation cleaves a bond homolytically, producing two radicals (Figure 2).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] This method is used most often with metal iodides, metal alkyls, and azo compounds.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Photoinitiation can also occur by bi-molecular H abstraction when the radical is in its lowest triplet excited state.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Reduction of hydrogen peroxide or an alkyl hydrogen peroxide by iron (Figure 3).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] can be employed in place of ferrous ion in many instances.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The dissociation of a persulfate in the aqueous phase (Figure 4).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] , in which the radical propagates initially in the water phase before entry into polymer particles (or self-collapsing to nucleate a particle).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The radical ions then initiate free radical (and/or ionic) polymerization.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] This type of initiation is especially useful for coating metal surfaces with polymer films.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] A gaseous monomer is placed in an electric discharge at low pressures under conditions where a plasma (ionized gaseous molecules) is created.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] (the formation and collapse of cavities in the liquid).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The collapse of the cavities generates very high local temperatures and pressures.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] This results in the formation of excited electronic states, which in turn lead to bond breakage and radical formation.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] initiator is the combination of several types of initiators into one initiating system.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The types of initiators are chosen based on the properties they are known to induce in the polymers they produce.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Metallocenes in combination with initiators accelerate polymerization of poly(methyl methacrylate) and produce a polymer with a narrower molecular weight distribution.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The example shown here consists of indenylzirconium (a metallocene) and benzoyl peroxide (an initiator).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The combination of all of these components—a metallocene, an initiator, and a heteroaromatic diketo carboxylic acid—yields a ternary initiating system that was shown to accelerate the polymerization and produce polymers with enhanced heat resistance and regular microstructure.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Due to side reactions, not all radicals formed by the dissociation of initiator molecules actually add monomers to form polymer chains.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The efficiency factor *f* is defined as the fraction of the original initiator which contributes to the polymerization reaction.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The maximal value of *f* is 1, but typical values range from 0.3 to 0.8.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The following types of reactions can decrease the efficiency of the initiator.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Two radicals recombine before initiating a chain (Figure 8).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] , meaning that no solvent has yet come between the new radicals.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] One radical is produced instead of the three radicals that could be produced (Figure 10).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] During polymerization, a polymer spends most of its time in increasing its chain length, or propagating.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] After the radical initiator is formed, it attacks a monomer (Figure 11).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] In an ethene monomer, one electron pair is held securely between the two carbons in a sigma bond.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The other is more loosely held in a pi bond.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The free radical uses one electron from the pi bond to form a more stable bond with the carbon atom.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The other electron returns to the second carbon atom, turning the whole molecule into another radical.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Figure 12 shows how the orbitals of an ethylene monomer interact with a radical initiator.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Once a chain has been initiated, the chain propagates (Figure 13) until there are no more monomers (living polymerization) or until termination occurs.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] There may be anywhere from a few to thousands of propagation steps depending on several factors such as radical and chain reactivity, the solvent, and temperature.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Chain termination is inevitable in radical polymerization due to the high reactivity of radicals.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Termination can occur by several different mechanisms.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] If longer chains are desired, the initiator concentration should be kept low; otherwise, many shorter chains will result.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Contrary to the other modes of termination, chain transfer results in the destruction of only one radical, but also the creation of another radical.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Often, however, this newly created radical is not capable of further propagation.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Similar to disproportionation, all chain-transfer mechanisms also involve the abstraction of a hydrogen or other atom.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] There are several types of chain-transfer mechanisms.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Also known as living radical polymerization, controlled radical polymerization, reversible deactivation radical polymerization (RDRP) relies on completely pure reactions, preventing termination caused by impurities.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Because these polymerizations stop only when there is no more monomer, polymerization can continue upon the addition of more monomer.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] RDRP allows for control of molecular weight and dispersity.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] However, this is very difficult to achieve and instead a pseudo-living polymerization occurs with only partial control of molecular weight and dispersity.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] ATRP and RAFT are the main types of complete radical polymerization.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] where *f* is the efficiency of the initiator and kd, kp, and kt are the constants for initiator dissociation, chain propagation and termination, respectively. [I] [M] and [M•] are the concentrations of the initiator, monomer and the active growing chain.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Under the steady-state approximation, the concentration of the active growing chains remains constant, i.e. the rates of initiation and of termination are equal.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The concentration of active chain can be derived and expressed in terms of the other known species in the system.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The kinetic chain length v is a measure of the average number of monomer units reacting with an active center during its lifetime and is related to the molecular weight through the mechanism of the termination.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Without chain transfer, the kinetic chain length is only a function of propagation rate and initiation rate.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Assuming no chain-transfer effect occurs in the reaction, the number average degree of polymerization Pn can be correlated with the kinetic chain length.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] If chain transfer is considered, the kinetic chain length is not affected by the transfer process because the growing free-radical center generated by the initiation step stays alive after any chain-transfer event, although multiple polymer chains are produced.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] However, the number average degree of polymerization decreases as the chain transfers, since the growing chains are terminated by the chain-transfer events.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Taking into account the chain-transfer reaction towards solvent *S*, initiator *I*, polymer *P*, and added chain-transfer agent *T*.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] In chain growth polymerization, the position of the equilibrium between polymer and monomers can be determined by the thermodynamics of the polymerization.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The Gibbs free energy (ΔGp) of the polymerization is commonly used to quantify the tendency of a polymeric reaction.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The polymerization will be favored if ΔGp < 0; if ΔGp > 0, the polymer will undergo depolymerization.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] According to the thermodynamic equation ΔG = ΔH – TΔS, a negative enthalpy and an increasing entropy will shift the equilibrium towards polymerization.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] In general, the polymerization is an exothermic process, i.e. negative enthalpy change, since addition of a monomer to the growing polymer chain involves the conversion of π bonds into σ bonds, or a ring–opening reaction that releases the ring tension in a cyclic monomer.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Meanwhile, during polymerization, a large amount of small molecules are associated, losing rotation and translational degrees of freedom.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] As a result, the entropy decreases in the system, ΔSp < 0 for nearly all polymerization processes.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Since depolymerization is almost always entropically favored, the ΔHp must then be sufficiently negative to compensate for the unfavorable entropic term.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Only then will polymerization be thermodynamically favored by the resulting negative ΔGp.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] In practice, polymerization is favored at low temperatures: TΔSp is small.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Depolymerization is favored at high temperatures: TΔSp is large.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] As the temperature increases, ΔGp become less negative.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] At a certain temperature, the polymerization reaches equilibrium (rate of polymerization = rate of depolymerization).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] This temperature is called the ceiling temperature (Tc). ΔGp = 0.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The stereochemistry of polymerization is concerned with the difference in atom connectivity and spatial orientation in polymers that has the same chemical composition.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Hermann Staudinger studied the stereoisomerism in chain polymerization of vinyl monomers in the late 1920s, and it took another two decades for people to fully appreciate the idea that each of the propagation steps in the polymer growth could give rise to stereoisomerism.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The major milestone in the stereochemistry was established by Ziegler and Natta and their coworkers in 1950s, as they developed metal based catalyst to synthesize stereoregular polymers.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The reason why the stereochemistry of the polymer is of particular interest is because the physical behavior of a polymer depends not only on the general chemical composition but also on the more subtle differences in microstructure.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Atactic polymers consist of a random arrangement of stereochemistry and are amorphous (noncrystalline), soft materials with lower physical strength.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The corresponding isotactic (like substituents all on the same side) and syndiotactic (like substituents of alternate repeating units on the same side) polymers are usually obtained as highly crystalline materials.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] It is easier for the stereoregular polymers to pack into a crystal lattice since they are more ordered and the resulting crystallinity leads to higher physical strength and increased solvent and chemical resistance as well as differences in other properties that depend on crystallinity.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The prime example of the industrial utility of stereoregular polymers is polypropene.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Isotactic polypropene is a high-melting (165 °C), strong, crystalline polymer, which is used as both a plastic and fiber.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Atactic polypropene is an amorphous material with an oily to waxy soft appearance that finds use in asphalt blends and formulations for lubricants, sealants, and adhesives, but the volumes are minuscule compared to that of isotactic polypropene.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] When a monomer adds to a radical chain end, there are two factors to consider regarding its stereochemistry: 1) the interaction between the terminal chain carbon and the approaching monomer molecule and 2) the configuration of the penultimate repeating unit in the polymer chain.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The terminal carbon atom has *sp2* hybridization and is planar.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Consider the polymerization of the monomer CH2=CXY.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] There are two ways that a monomer molecule can approach the terminal carbon: the mirror approach (with like substituents on the same side) or the non-mirror approach (like substituents on opposite sides).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] If free rotation does not occur before the next monomer adds, the mirror approach will always lead to an isotactic polymer and the non-mirror approach will always lead to a syndiotactic polymer (Figure 25).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] However, if interactions between the substituents of the penultimate repeating unit and the terminal carbon atom are significant, then conformational factors could cause the monomer to add to the polymer in a way that minimizes steric or electrostatic interaction (Figure 26).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Traditionally, the reactivity of monomers and radicals are assessed by the means of copolymerization data.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The *Q–e* scheme, the most widely used tool for the semi-quantitative prediction of monomer reactivity ratios, was first proposed by Alfrey and Price in 1947.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The scheme takes into account the intrinsic thermodynamic stability and polar effects in the transition state.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] A given radical $M_{i}^{o}$ and a monomer $M_{j}$ are considered to have intrinsic reactivities Pi and Qj, respectively.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The polar effects in the transition state, the supposed permanent electric charge carried by that entity (radical or molecule), is quantified by the factor *e*, which is a constant for a given monomer, and has the same value for the radical derived from that specific monomer.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] For the copolymerization of a given pair of monomers, the two experimental reactivity ratios r1 and r2 permit the evaluation of (Q1/Q2) and (e1 – e2).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Values for each monomer can then be assigned relative to a reference monomer, usually chosen as styrene with the arbitrary values Q = 1.0 and e = –0.8.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Free radical polymerization has found applications including the manufacture of polystyrene, thermoplastic block copolymer elastomers, cardiovascular stents, chemical surfactants and lubricants.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Block copolymers are used for a wide variety of applications including adhesives, footwear and toys.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Free radical polymerization allows the functionalization of carbon nanotubes.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] CNTs intrinsic electronic properties lead them to form large aggregates in solution, precluding useful applications.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Adding small chemical groups to the walls of CNT can eliminate this propensity and tune the response to the surrounding environment.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] The use of polymers instead of smaller molecules can modify CNT properties (and conversely, nanotubes can modify polymer mechanical and electronic properties).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] For example, researchers coated carbon nanotubes with polystyrene by first polymerizing polystyrene via chain radical polymerization and subsequently mixing it at 130 °C with carbon nanotubes to generate radicals and graft them onto the walls of carbon nanotubes (Figure 27).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Chain growth polymerization ("grafting to") synthesizes a polymer with predetermined properties.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Purification of the polymer can be used to obtain a more uniform length distribution before grafting.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Conversely, “grafting from”, with radical polymerization techniques such as atom transfer radical polymerization (ATRP) or nitroxide-mediated polymerization (NMP), allows rapid growth of high molecular weight polymers.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Radical polymerization also aids synthesis of nanocomposite hydrogels.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] These gels are made of water-swellable nano-scale clay (especially those classed as smectites) enveloped by a network polymer.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Aqueous dispersions of clay are treated with an initiator and a catalyst and the organic monomer, generally an acrylamide.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Polymers grow off the initiators that are in turn bound to the clay.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Due to recombination and disproportionation reactions, growing polymer chains bind to one another, forming a strong, cross-linked network polymer, with clay particles acting as branching points for multiple polymer chain segments.
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Free radical polymerization used in this context allows the synthesis of polymers from a wide variety of substrates (the chemistries of suitable clays vary).
[src:polymerization/radical-polymerization] Termination reactions unique to chain growth polymerization produce a material with flexibility, mechanical strength and biocompatibility.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] In polymer chemistry, **step-growth polymerization** is a type of polymerization mechanism in which bi-functional or multifunctional monomers react to form first dimers, then trimers, longer oligomers, and eventually long-chain polymers.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Many naturally occurring and some synthetic polymers are produced by step-growth polymerization, such as polyesters, polyamides, polyurethanes, etc.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Due to the nature of the polymerization mechanism, a high extent of reaction is required to achieve high molecular weight.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The easiest way to visualize the mechanism of a step-growth polymerization is a group of people reaching out to hold their hands to form a human chain—each person has two hands (reactive sites).
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] There also is the possibility to have more than two reactive sites on a monomer: In this case branched-polymer production takes place.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Most natural polymers employed at early stages of human society are of condensation type.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The synthesis of first truly synthetic polymeric material, bakelite, was announced by Leo Baekeland in 1907, through a typical step-growth polymerization fashion of phenol and formaldehyde.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The pioneer of synthetic polymer science, Wallace Carothers, developed a new means of making polyesters through step-growth polymerization in 1930s as a research group leader at DuPont.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] It was the first reaction designed and carried out with the specific purpose of creating high-molecular-weight polymer molecules, as well as the first polymerization reaction whose results had been predicted by scientific theory.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Carothers developed a series of mathematical equations to describe the behavior of step-growth polymerization systems which are still known as the Carothers equations today.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Collaborating with Paul Flory, a physical chemist, they developed theories that describe more mathematical aspects of step-growth polymerization including kinetics, stoichiometry, molecular-weight distribution, etc.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Carothers is also well-known for his invention of Nylon.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Step-growth polymerization and **condensation polymerization** are two different concepts, not always identical.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] In fact polyurethane polymerizes with addition polymerization (because its polymerization produces no small molecules), but its reaction mechanism corresponds to a step-growth polymerization.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] This technique is usually compared with chain-growth polymerization to show its characteristics.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] A monomer with functionality of 3 or more will introduce branching in a polymer and will ultimately form a cross-linked macrostructure or network even at low fractional conversion.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The point at which a tree-like topology transits to a network is known as the gel point because it is signalled by an abrupt change in viscosity.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] One of the earliest so-called thermosets is known as Bakelite.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] It is not always water that is released in step-growth polymerization: in acyclic diene metathesis or ADMET, dienes polymerize with loss of ethene.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The kinetics and rates of step-growth polymerization can be described using a polyesterification mechanism.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The simple esterification is an acid-catalyzed process in which protonation of the acid is followed by interaction with the alcohol to produce an ester and water.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] However, there are a few assumptions needed with this kinetic model.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The first assumption is water (or any other condensation product) is efficiently removed.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Secondly, the functional group reactivities are independent of chain length.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Finally, it is assumed that each step only involves one alcohol and one acid.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] This is a general rate law degree of polymerization for polyesterification, where *n* is the reaction order.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] If no acid catalyst is added, the reaction will still proceed because the acid can act as its own catalyst.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The second-order [COOH] term arises from its use as a catalyst, and *k* is the rate constant.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] For a self-catalyzed system, the *number average degree of polymerization* (*X*n) grows proportionally with ${\sqrt {t}}$ .
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The uncatalyzed reaction is rather slow, and a high *X*n is not readily attained.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] which is kinetically first-order in each functional group.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] For an externally catalyzed system, the number average degree of polymerization grows proportionally with *t*.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The product of a polymerization is a mixture of polymer molecules of different molecular weights.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] For theoretical and practical reasons, it is of interest to discuss the distribution of molecular weights in a polymerization.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The molecular weight distribution (MWD) had been derived by Flory by a statistical approach based on the concept of equal reactivity of functional groups.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Step-growth polymerization is a random process, so we can use statistics to calculate the probability of finding a chain with x-structural units ("x-mer") as a function of time or conversion.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The probability that an A functional group has reacted is $p^{x-1}$ , and the probability of finding an A unreacted is $(1-p)$ .
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] where *Px* is the probability of finding a chain that is *x* units long and has an unreacted A.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] As *x* increases, the probability decreases.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] where *N* is the total number of polymer molecules present in the reaction.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Therefore, in step-growth when *p*=1, then the PDI=2.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] There are two important aspects with regard to the control of molecular weight in polymerization.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] In the synthesis of polymers, one is usually interested in obtaining a product of very specific molecular weight, since the properties of the polymer will usually be highly dependent on molecular weight.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Molecular weights higher or lower than the desired weight are equally undesirable.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Since the degree of polymerization is a function of reaction time, the desired molecular weight can be obtained by quenching the reaction at the appropriate time.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] However, the polymer obtained in this manner is unstable, in that it leads to changes in molecular weight because the ends of the polymer molecule contain functional groups that can react further with each other.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] This situation is avoided by adjusting the concentrations of the two monomers so that they are slightly nonstoichiometric.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] One of the reactants is present in slight excess.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The polymerization then proceeds to a point at which one reactant is completely used up and all the chain ends possess the same functional group of the group that is in excess.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Further polymerization is not possible, and the polymer is stable to subsequent molecular-weight changes.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Another method of achieving the desired molecular weight is by addition of a small amount of monofunctional monomer, a monomer with only one functional group.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The monofunctional monomer, often referred to as a chain stopper, controls and limits the polymerization of bifunctional monomers because the growing polymer yields chain ends devoid of functional groups and therefore incapable of further reaction.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] To properly control the polymer molecular weight, the stoichiometric imbalance of the bifunctional monomer or the monofunctional monomer must be precisely adjusted.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] If the nonstoichiometric imbalance is too large, the polymer molecular weight will be too low.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] It is important to understand the quantitative effect of the stoichiometric imbalance of reactants on the molecular weight.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Also, this is necessary in order to know the quantitative effect of any reactive impurities that may be present in the reaction mixture either initially or that are formed by undesirable side reactions.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Impurities with A or B functional groups may drastically lower the polymer molecular weight unless their presence is quantitatively taken into account.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] More usefully, a precisely controlled stoichiometric imbalance of the reactants in the mixture can provide the desired result.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] For example, an excess of diamine over an acid chloride would eventually produce a polyamide with two amine end groups incapable of further growth when the acid chloride was totally consumed.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] where *NB* is the number of monofunction molecules added.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The coefficient of 2 in front of *NB* is required since one B molecule has the same quantitative effect as one excess B-B molecule.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] A monomer with functionality 3 has 3 functional groups that participate in the polymerization.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] This will introduce branching in a polymer and may ultimately form a cross-linked macrostructure.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The point at which this three-dimensional 3D network is formed is known as the gel point, signaled by an abrupt change in viscosity.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] A more general functionality factor *fav* is defined for multi-chain polymerization, as the average number of functional groups present per monomer unit.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] For a system containing *N*0 molecules initially and equivalent numbers of two function groups A and B, the total number of functional groups is *N*0*fav*.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The driving force in designing new polymers is the prospect of replacing other materials of construction, especially metals, by using lightweight and heat-resistant polymers.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Polymer chains based on aromatic rings are desirable due to high bond strengths and rigid polymer chains.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] High molecular weight and crosslinking are desirable for the same reason.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Strong dipole-dipole interactions, hydrogen bonds, and crystallinity also improve heat resistance.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] To obtain desired mechanical strength, sufficiently high molecular weights are necessary, however, decreased solubility is a problem.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] One approach to solve this problem is to introduce of some flexibilizing linkages, such as isopropylidene, C=O, and SO2 into the rigid polymer chain by using an appropriate monomer or comonomer.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Another approach involves the synthesis of reactive telechelic oligomers containing functional end-groups capable of reacting with each other; polymerization of the oligomer gives higher molecular weight, referred to as chain extension.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The oxidative coupling polymerization of many 2,6-disubstituted phenols using a catalytic complex of a cuprous salt and amine form aromatic polyethers, commercially referred to as poly(p-phenylene oxide) or PPO.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Neat PPO has little commercial uses due to its high melt viscosity.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Its available products are blends of PPO with high-impact polystyrene (HIPS).
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Polyethersulfone (PES) is also referred to as polyetherketone and polysulfone.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] It is synthesized by nucleophilic aromatic substitution between aromatic dihalides and bisphenolate salts.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Polyethersulfones are partially crystalline and highly resistant to a wide range of aqueous and organic environments.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] They are rated for continuous service at temperatures of 240–280 °C.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The polyketones are finding applications in areas like automotive, aerospace, electrical-electronic cable insulation.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Poly(p-phenylene sulfide) (PPS) is synthesized by the reaction of sodium sulfide with p-dichlorobenzene in a polar solvent such as 1-methyl-2-pyrrolidinone (NMP).
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] It is inherently flame-resistant and stable toward organic and aqueous conditions; however, it is somewhat susceptible to oxidants.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Applications of PPS include automotive, microwave oven components, coatings for cookware when blended with fluorocarbon polymers, and protective coatings for valves, pipes, electromotive cells, etc.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Aromatic polyimides are synthesized by the reaction of dianhydrides with diamines, such as pyromellitic anhydride with *p*-phenylenediamine.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] It can also be accomplished using diisocyanates in place of diamines.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Solubility considerations sometimes suggest use of the half acid-half ester of the dianhydride, instead of the dianhydride itself.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Polymerization is accomplished by a two-stage process due to the insolubility of polyimides.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The first stage forms a soluble and fusible high-molecular-weight poly(amic acid) in a polar aprotic solvent such as NMP or N,N-dimethylacetamide.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The poly(amic aicd) can then be processed into the desired physical form of the final polymer product (e.g., film, fiber, laminate, coating) which is insoluble and infusible.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The telechelic oligomer approach applies the usual polymerization manner except that one includes a monofunctional reactant to stop reaction at the oligomer stage, generally in the 50–3000 molecular weight.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] The monofunctional reactant not only limits polymerization but end-caps the oligomer with functional groups capable of subsequent reaction to achieve curing of the oligomer.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Functional groups like alkyne, norbornene, maleimide, nitrite, and cyanate have been used for this purpose.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Maleimide and norbornene end-capped oligomers can be cured by heating.
[src:polymerization/step-growth-polymerization] Alkyne, nitrile, and cyanate end-capped oligomers can undergo cyclotrimerization, yielding aromatic structures.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] A **Ziegler–Natta catalyst**, named after Karl Ziegler and Giulio Natta, is a catalyst used in the synthesis of polymers of 1-alkenes (alpha-olefins).
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The 1963 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to German Karl Ziegler, for his discovery of first titanium-based catalysts, and Italian Giulio Natta, for using them to prepare stereoregular polymers from propylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Ziegler–Natta catalysts have been used in the commercial manufacture of various polyolefins since 1956.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] As of 2010, the total volume of plastics, elastomers, and rubbers produced from alkenes with these and related (especially Phillips) catalysts worldwide exceeds 100 million tonnes.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Together, these polymers represent the largest-volume commodity plastics as well as the largest-volume commodity chemicals in the world.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] In the early 1950s workers at Phillips Petroleum discovered that chromium catalysts are highly effective for the low-temperature polymerization of ethylene, which launched major industrial technologies culminating in the Phillips catalyst.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] A few years later, Ziegler discovered that a combination of titanium tetrachloride (TiCl4) and diethylaluminium chloride (Al(C2H5)2Cl) gave comparable activities for the production of polyethylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Natta used crystalline α-TiCl3 in combination with Al(C2H5)3 to produce first isotactic polypropylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Usually Ziegler catalysts refer to titanium-based systems for conversions of ethylene and Ziegler–Natta catalysts refer to systems for conversions of propylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Also, in the 1960s, BASF developed a gas-phase, mechanically-stirred polymerization process for making polypropylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] In that process, the particle bed in the reactor was either not fluidized or not fully fluidized.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] In 1968, the first gas-phase fluidized-bed polymerization process, the Unipol process, was commercialized by Union Carbide to produce polyethylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] In the mid-1980s, the Unipol process was further extended to produce polypropylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] In the 1970s, magnesium chloride (MgCl2) was discovered to greatly enhance the activity of the titanium-based catalysts.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The fluidized-bed process remains one of the two most widely used processes for producing polypropylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Natta first used polymerization catalysts based on titanium chlorides to polymerize propylene and other 1-alkenes.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] He discovered that these polymers are crystalline materials and ascribed their crystallinity to a special feature of the polymer structure called stereoregularity.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The concept of stereoregularity in polymer chains is illustrated in the picture on the left with polypropylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Stereoregular poly(1-alkene) can be isotactic or syndiotactic depending on the relative orientation of the alkyl groups in polymer chains consisting of units −[CH2−CHR]−, like the CH3 groups in the figure.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] In the isotactic polymers, all stereogenic centers CHR share the same configuration.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The stereogenic centers in syndiotactic polymers alternate their relative configuration.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] A polymer that lacks any regular arrangement in the position of its alkyl substituents (R) is called atactic.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Both isotactic and syndiotactic polypropylene are crystalline, whereas atactic polypropylene, which can also be prepared with special Ziegler–Natta catalysts, is amorphous.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Ultimately, the stereoregularity of the polymer is determined by the catalyst used to prepare it.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Most polymers produced with a Ziegler-Natta catalyst are enantioselective site-controlled, meaning the stereochemistry of each added monomer is dependent primarily on the stereochemistry of the catalyst (barring stereo errors) rather than the stereochemistry of the previous monomer.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Thus, the chirality of the catalyst greatly influences tacticity.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] For example, achiral bis(2-phenylindenyl)zirconium dichloride produces isotactic polymers whereas its chiral variant produces syndiotactic polymers.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The attachment of bulky ligands to the metal center results in steric hindrance, designed to restrict the orientation from which the incoming alkene can attack the metal center.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Unique behaviors of the catalyst can also strongly impact tacticity.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] For example, the open site of VCl4/Al(C2H5)2Cl alternates between the axial and equatorial site with every monomer addition.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] As a result, each successive propylene monomer will insert into the vanadium-carbon bond from opposite sides.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The alternating active site geometry thus produces a polymer chain with alternating enantiomeric configurations, producing syndiotactic polypropylene.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] See #Mechanism of Ziegler–Natta polymerization for the detailed mechanism.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The overlap between these two subclasses is relatively small because the requirements to the respective catalysts differ widely.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Commercial catalysts are supported by being bound to a solid with a high surface area.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Both TiCl4 and TiCl3 give active catalysts.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The support in the majority of the catalysts is MgCl2.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] A third component of most catalysts is a carrier, a material that determines the size and the shape of catalyst particles.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The preferred carrier is microporous spheres of amorphous silica with a diameter of 30–40 mm.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] During the catalyst synthesis, both the titanium compounds and MgCl2 are packed into the silica pores.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] All these catalysts are activated with organoaluminum compounds such as Al(C2H5)3.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] All modern supported Ziegler–Natta catalysts designed for polymerization of propylene and higher 1-alkenes are prepared with TiCl4 as the active ingredient and MgCl2 as a support.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Another component of all such catalysts is an organic modifier, usually an ester of an aromatic diacid or a diether.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The modifiers react both with inorganic ingredients of the solid catalysts as well as with organoaluminum cocatalysts.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] These catalysts polymerize propylene and other 1-alkenes to highly crystalline isotactic polymers.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] A second class of Ziegler–Natta catalysts are soluble in the reaction medium.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Traditionally such homogeneous catalysts were derived from metallocenes, but the structures of active catalysts have been significantly broadened to include nitrogen-based ligands.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] These catalysts are metallocenes together with a cocatalyst, typically MAO, −[O−Al(CH3)]*n*−.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The idealized metallocene catalysts have the composition Cp2MCl2 (M = Ti, Zr, Hf) such as titanocene dichloride.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Typically, the organic ligands are derivatives of cyclopentadienyl.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] In some complexes, the two cyclopentadiene (Cp) rings are linked with bridges, like −CH2−CH2− or >SiPh2.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Depending on the type of their cyclopentadienyl ligands, for example by using an *ansa*-bridge, metallocene catalysts can produce either isotactic or syndiotactic polymers of propylene and other 1-alkenes.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Metallocenes are referred to as single-site catalysts, where the active site across each metallocene complex is structurally identical.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The surface of a heterogeneous catalyst is not uniform, so there are many different active sites with differing electronic environments.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] As the structure of the active site directly affects the stereoregularity and tacticity, heterogeneous catalysts may produce polymers with a broader range of tacticities.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Metallocenes do not suffer from this weakness, and so often result in polymers with greater stereoregularity and narrower molecular weight distributions.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The chirality of the metallocene is a major determinant in whether the polymer is isotactic or syndiotactic.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Ziegler–Natta catalysts of the third class, non-metallocene catalysts, use a variety of complexes of various metals, ranging from scandium to lanthanoid and actinoid metals, and a large variety of ligands containing oxygen (O2), nitrogen (N2), phosphorus (P), and sulfur (S).
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The complexes are activated using MAO, as is done for metallocene catalysts.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Most Ziegler–Natta catalysts and all the alkylaluminium cocatalysts are unstable in air, and the alkylaluminium compounds are pyrophoric.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The catalysts, therefore, are always prepared and handled under an inert atmosphere.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The structure of active centers in Ziegler–Natta catalysts is well established only for metallocene catalysts.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] An idealized and simplified metallocene complex Cp2ZrCl2 represents a typical precatalyst.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The dihalide reacts with MAO and is transformed into a metallocenium ion Cp2+ZrCH3, which is ion-paired to some derivative(s) of MAO.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Many thousands of alkene insertion reactions occur at each active center resulting in the formation of long polymer chains attached to the center.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The Cossee–Arlman mechanism describes the growth of stereospecific polymers.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] This mechanism states that the polymer grows through alkene coordination at a vacant site at the titanium atom, which is followed by insertion of the C=C bond into the Ti−C bond at the active center.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Upon coordination of the alkene to the catalyst, the alkene donates electrons from its pi-bonding orbital into the metal center's empty d orbital while also accepting electrons from the metal's filled d orbitals into its empty pi anti-bonding orbital.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The synergy of these interactions stabilize the overall bond between the alkene and metal center and thus facilitates initial coordination.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] On occasion, the polymer chain is disengaged from the active centers in the chain termination reaction.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Polymerization reactions of alkenes with solid titanium-based catalysts occur at special titanium centers located on the exterior of the catalyst crystallites.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Some titanium atoms in these crystallites react with organoaluminum cocatalysts with the formation of Ti–C bonds.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] The two chain termination reactions occur quite rarely in Ziegler–Natta catalysis and the formed polymers have a too high molecular weight to be of commercial use.
[src:polymerization/ziegler-natta-catalyst] Another termination process involves the action of protic (acidic) reagents, which can be intentionally added or adventitious.
